# ITI–gITI–IDI Framework

This repository documents the ITI–gITI–IDI framework, a computational model for measuring institutional distortion between expected institutional strain and realized outcome patterns.

The framework separates three layers:

## 1. ITI — Institutional Tension Index

ITI is the policy-side or budget-side estimator. It is computed from planning, funding, allocation, budget, authorization, and institutional expectation data.

It represents the strain that a system expects, permits, or builds into its formal design.

## 2. gITI — Geometric Institutional Tension Index

gITI is the outcome-side geometric estimator. It is extracted from realized data after the system operates.

It captures observed tension through spatial distribution, clustering, density, concentration, gap formation, and other geometric patterns in actual outcomes.

## 3. IDI — Institutional Distortion Index

IDI measures the absolute gap between ITI and gITI:

IDI = |ITI - gITI|

IDI functions as a distortion signal. It shows the difference between what the system expected and what the system actually produced.

## Applied Case Pathway

The first applied case pathway in this repository is the Lehman Brothers case.

The purpose is to collect public data, map expected institutional strain, extract realized geometric tension, and calculate a preliminary institutional distortion signal.

## Repository Status

This repository is an early working model repository. It is intended to support future data collection, variable mapping, index construction, and case-based institutional analysis.
